object_dating_comment.0: The wreck itself is dated by lamps, terra-sigillata and a coin (As by Sextus Pompeius, minted between 45 und 27 BCE)
object_dating_comment.3: According to Franken, the bust of Mars is related to the steelyard. By the use of stylistic criteria, the bust is assumpted to be from late Republican to early Augustan period.
object_dating_comment.4: Motive of sliding-weight belonging to Roman imperial period
object_dating_comment.6: Based on the dating by Franken due to characteristic features of the balance although some stylistic criteria (if the sliding-weight belongs genuinely to the balance) point to a later date in the middle of the first century AD.
object_dating_comment.7: The inscription mentions the second consulate of Lucius Verus with Marcus Aurelius as his senior partner from 161 CE. Gauging inscription likely to have been applied only after balance had been in use for considerable period of time.
object_dating_comment.9: We assume that the object is  from one of the Vesuvian towns. Hence the fixed enddate
object_dating_comment.10: Gauging inscription of 47 CE. Cf. ID 0040.
object_dating_comment.13: Gauging inscription of 47 CE. Cf. ID 0020.
object_dating_comment.14: Based on stylistic criteria Franken dates the sliding weight to the Tiberian period, cf. ID 0046.
object_dating_comment.16: According to stylistic criteria, the bust is assumed (Franken) to date to Tiberian period, cf. ID 0044.
object_dating_comment.17: Probably end of 1st to beginning of 2nd cent. CE
object_dating_comment.18: Found in layer together with pottery; pottery dates neronian to early flavian: 60-75 CE
object_dating_comment.24: Building sacrifice during the construction of the wooden fort about 90 CE (Grönke 1990, 10)
object_dating_comment.25: Dated by few associated finds to the 1st cent. CE (Mutz 1983, 35)
object_dating_comment.26: The Roman fort Osterburken existed from 160 CE to 260 CE
object_dating_comment.35: The bust (if it belongs genuinely to the steelyard) can be dated (based on stylistic criteria by Franken) around 550 CE
object_dating_comment.38: Franken (8NKC882F) dates the sliding-weight to late first early second century CE. The sliding-weight has a separate inventory number and possibly doesn’t belong to balance.
object_dating_comment.40: Bendeguz (in SIA34PXI) dates the balance to the 9th century CE based on a comperandum from Corinth from a secure context
object_dating_comment.43: The ship wreck is dated to the 6th or 7th century. The inscriptions are dated based on stylistic reasons to the 6th century.
object_dating_comment.46: Occupation time of roman fort from around 150 to 260 CE
object_dating_comment.48: Occupation time of roman fort from 110 to 270 CE
object_dating_comment.49: Well filled after fire disaster (Planck 1983, 153); timbers out of the filling of the well dated by dendrochronology; well could be filled only after 255 CE; abandonment of the vicus 260 CE (Planck 1983, 156)
object_dating_comment.50: Balance dated on the basis of similarities to iron balances type „Gilly-sur-Isère“
object_dating_comment.65: The balance was part of the Hamilton collection. Hamilton formed his collection as British envoy to Naples between 1764 and 1798. The balance supposedly stems from the contemporary excavations of Pompeji or Herculaneum.
object_dating_comment.80: Latest coin dates 625/626 CE, ship foundered a few years later
object_dating_comment.81: Dwelling inhabited from 5th to 6th cent. CE (Knific 1991, 21)
object_dating_comment.92: Latest coin dates 625/626 CE, ship foundered a few years later
object_dating_comment.108: Dwelling inhabited from 3rd to 6th cent. CE (Knific 1979, 761-762)
object_dating_comment.109: Dwelling inhabited from 3rd to 6th cent. CE (Knific 1979, 761-762)
object_dating_comment.121: Early to middle imperial period (ca. 50-276 CE). The gallo-roman vicus at Schwarzenacker was completely destroyed by the Alemanni in 276 CE.
object_dating_comment.122: Grave dated by the end of the fifth century
object_dating_comment.123: Grave dated by first half of 5th cent.
object_dating_comment.128: Found within the filling of the space for firing of a pottery kiln; main working period of this pottery kiln: 2nd cent. CE; the pottery kiln and the whole pottery workshop was rendered at the end of 2nd cent. CE
object_dating_comment.130: Not later than the 12th century CE
object_dating_comment.133: Early byzantine, 1st half of 5th cent. CE
object_dating_comment.143: The dating of the hoard by Feugère to the end of the 2nd cent. BCE is based upon the shapes of the bronze vessels by comparison with a hoard found at Parma. Possibly an indication for an earlier dating of the typ of Valle Ponti, but the bronze vessels from the  hoard found at Agde could have been used for a long time before beeing hoarded.
object_dating_comment.153: Find context (hoard) dates to the 4th century CE, maybe to the end of the 4th century CE
object_dating_comment.154: Hoard dates 2nd half 4th cent. to 1st half 5th cent. CE (Bozic 2005, 356)
object_dating_comment.155: 2nd half of 4th century CE (Bass et al. 1971, 37)
object_dating_comment.156: Latest coin dates 625/626 CE, ship foundered a few years later
object_dating_comment.157: Dating of the find context is around 30 BCE to 280 CE
object_dating_comment.164: Found within an ash layer of a roman villa; roman villa is dated 2nd half of 2nd cent. CE
object_dating_comment.165: Occupation time of roman fort from 90 to 260 CE
object_dating_comment.166: Occupation time of roman fort from 90 to 260 CE
object_dating_comment.167: Dating of the necropolis: beginning of 1st cent. to 2nd half of 2nd cent. CE
